0–1440","1345":"1345","1421":"1421","1440":"1440","1460":"1460","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1408":"1408","1419":"1419","1392":"1392","1380":"1380","Abt 1404":"about 1404","Leicestershire, England":"Leicestershire, England","Sedgebrook, Lincolnshire, England":"Sedgebrook, Lincolnshire, England","Shrewsbury, Shropshire, England, slain in battle":"Shrewsbury, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","Sedgebrook, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Sedgebrook, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bourdon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French:","nickname from Old French <i>bourdon</i>, a word with several meanings, from any or each of which the surname could have arisen: ‘pilgrim's staff’, denoting a pilgrim; ‘bumblebee’, denoting someone thought to resemble the insect in some way; and ‘bagpipes’, denoting a piper or pipe-maker. It is also found in England, as a surname of Huguenot origin (compare   Burden  ).","habitational name from (Le) Bourdon, the name of several places in various parts of France."],"variants":[{"name":"Bourdo","meanings":["Altered form of French   Bourdon  ."]},{"name":"Burden","meanings":["English:","(southern England, of Norman origin): from a diminutive of the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Burdo</i>, for which compare   Burdett  . <i>Burdonus</i> and other derivatives of the Gaulish personal name <i>Burdo</i> (‘mule’) are found in France, where it is rare and the similar French surname may derive instead from Old French <i>bourdon</i> in the sense ‘pilgrim's staff’ (compare   Bourdon   1). The personal name, whether of ancient Germanic or Gaulish origin, does occur in medieval England, but rarely.","habitational name from any of various places called Burdon or Burden. Burden in Yorkshire and Great Burdon in County Durham are named with Old English <i>burh</i> ‘stronghold, fortified place’ + <i>dūn</i> ‘hill’; Burdon in Tyne and Wear is named with Old English <i>b̄re</i> ‘byre’ + <i>denu</i> ‘valley’."]}]},{"name":"Sir","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Simon  , now rare, but more common in the Middle Ages, when it gave rise to the surnames <i>Simms</i> and <i>Simpson</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Simon","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."]}]},{"name":"Nicholas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Nickolas","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: variant spelling of   Nicholas  , influenced by the short form   Nick ."]},{"name":"Nicolas","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":2,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Nicholas Bourdon was born in 1380, in Leicestershire, England, his father, Sir John Bourdon VI, was 20 and his mother, Lady Elizabeth Millicent Beckering x, was 35. He married Lady Elizabeth Millicent Beckering x in 1408, in Sedgebrook, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1408, in Shrewsbury, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 28."},"et":{"1380–1408":"1380–1408","1382–Male":"1382–Surnud","1392–1421":"1392–1421","1345–1419":"1345–1419","1408–1460":"1408–1460","1360–1440":"1360–1440","1345":"1345","1421":"1421","1440":"1440","1460":"1460","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1408":"1408","1419":"1419","1392":"1392","1380":"1380","Abt 1404":"umbes 1404","Leicestershire, England":"Leicestershire, England","Sedgebrook, Lincolnshire, England":"Sedgebrook, Lincolnshire, England","Shrewsbury, Shropshire, England, slain in battle":"Shrewsbury, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Sedgebrook, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Sedgebrook, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1380–1408":"1380–1408","1382–Male":"1382–Kuollut","1392–1421":"1392–1421","1345–1419":"1345–1419","1408–1460":"1408–1460","1360–1440":"1360–1440","1345":"1345","1421":"1421","1440":"1440","1460":"1460","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1408":"1408","1419":"1419","1392":"1392","1380":"1380","Abt 1404":"noin 1404","Leicestershire, England":"Leicestershire, England","Sedgebrook, Lincolnshire, England":"Sedgebrook, Lincolnshire, England","Shrewsbury, Shropshire, England, slain in battle":"Shrewsbury, Shropshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Sedgebrook, Lincol